of   Bradshaw  , reflecting the local Yorkshire pronunciation."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William Bradshaw was born in 1314, in Swillington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She married William Bradshaw about 1339, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1314–":"1314–Surnud","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1314–Female":"1314–Surnud","1314":"1314","about 1339":"umbes 1339","1355":"1355","about 1355":"umbes 1355","of Nether, Swillington, Yorkshire, England":"Swillington, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Nether, Swillington, West Riding of Yorkshire,n England":"Swillington, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1314–":"1314–Kuollut","1314–Male":"1314–Kuollut","1355–Female":"1355–Kuollut","1314–Female":"1314–Kuollut","1314":"1314","about 1339":"noin 1339","1355":"1355","about 1355":"noin 1355","of Nether, Swillington, Yorkshire, England":"Swillington, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Nether, Swillington, West Riding of Yorkshire,n England":"Swillington, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engl